    <title id="1">Configuring Controller-0</title>
    <shortdesc id="2">You can configure <nameliteral id="3">controller-0</nameliteral> by running a script from
        the Linux command line.</shortdesc>
    <prolog>
        <author id="4">Jim Owens</author>
        <author id="5">Pedro Sanchez</author>
        <author id="6">Tom Towle</author>
    </prolog>
    <taskbody>
        <prereq id="prereq_N1002B_N10028_N10001" id="7">
            <p id="8">Before running the configuration script:</p>
            <ul id="ul_hk2_wmr_g4">
                <li id="9">
                    <p id="10">Ensure that <nameliteral id="144">controller-0</nameliteral> has been
                        initialized, as described in <xref href="jow1404333490251.xml" id="12"/>.</p>
                </li>
                <li id="145">
                    <p id="146">Ensure that the management interface on
                            <nameliteral id="147">controller-0</nameliteral> is connected and
                        operational.</p>
                </li>
                <li id="202">
                    <p id="203">Install system software patches if there are any available from Wind
                        River.</p>
                </li>
                <li id="13">
                    <p id="14">Prepare a configuration plan to use as a reference. For
                        details, see  the <cite id="15">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade Administration
                            Guide: Storage Planning</cite>.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </prereq>
        <!-- context id="context_N1007D_N1002E_N10001" id="282">
            <p id="283">For a minimal two-server configuration, in which the controller and
                compute functions are combined on a single host, the procedure varies slightly. The
                compute function on <nameliteral id="284">controller-0</nameliteral> is
                configured before the <nameliteral id="285">controller-1</nameliteral>
                configuration is started. This allows the first host to be fully configured without
                requiring a swact to lock it.</p>
        </context -->
        <steps>
            <step id="step_N10102_N10031_N1001E_N10001" id="201">
                <cmd id="232">Copy the license file to the controller node.</cmd>
                <substeps id="substeps_rqq_nn2_hq">
                    <substep id="235">
                        <cmd id="193">Connect the controller to the OAM network.</cmd>
                        <info id="234">
                            <p id="237">On the controller, assign the correct OAM network
                                address to the appropriate port.</p>
                            <codeblock id="239"><systemoutput id="259">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="272">sudo ip addr add <varname id="215">OAM_IP_address/mask</varname> dev <varname id="218">port</varname></userinput>
<systemoutput id="313">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="316">sudo ip link set <varname id="319">port</varname> up</userinput>
<systemoutput id="314">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="317">sudo route add default gw <varname id="320">gateway_addr</varname></userinput></codeblock>
                            <note id="note_N10139_N10115_N1010C_N10108_N10101_N10031_N1001E_N10001" id="222">
                                <p id="223">To identify the controller-0 port and IP
                                    address, refer to your OAM network plan.</p>
                            </note>
                        </info>
                        <stepxmp id="224">
                            <p id="225">For example:</p>
                            <codeblock id="241"><systemoutput id="261">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="274">sudo ip addr add 10.10.10.3/24 dev eth0</userinput>
<systemoutput id="262">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="275">sudo ip link set eth0 up</userinput>
<systemoutput id="315">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="318">sudo route add default gw 10.10.10.1</userinput></codeblock>
                        </stepxmp>
                    </substep>
                    <substep id="226">
                        <cmd id="227">Connect a server containing the license file to the
                            OAM network.</cmd>
                    </substep>
                    <substep id="243">
                        <cmd id="126">Copy the HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade license file to <filepath id="127">/home/wrsroot/license.lic</filepath> on the
                            controller.</cmd>
                        <info id="245">
                            <p id="246">This is the default path offered during controller
                                configuration. If you prefer, you can copy the file to a different
                                path, and specify the path during configuration.</p>
                        </info>
                        <stepxmp id="329">
                            <codeblock id="331"><systemoutput id="333">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="335">scp <varname id="337">username</varname>@<varname id="339">sourcehost</varname>:<varname id="341">sourcepath</varname>/license.lic /home/wrsroot/license.lic</userinput></codeblock>
                        </stepxmp>
                    </substep>
                </substeps>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N1015F_N10092_N1002E_N10001" importance="optional" id="343">
                <cmd id="344">Copy a digital certificate file to the controller node. </cmd>
                <info id="345">
                    <p id="346">If you require secure REST API access using HTTPS, copy a
                        CA-signed digital certificate (PEM file) to a directory on the controller.
                        The recommended path is <filepath id="350">/home/wrsroot</filepath>.</p>
                </info>
                <stepxmp id="330">
                    <codeblock id="332"><systemoutput id="334">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="336">scp <varname id="338">username</varname>@<varname id="340">sourcehost</varname>:<varname id="342">sourcepath</varname>/<varname id="351">pem_file</varname> /home/wrsroot/<varname id="352">pem_file</varname></userinput></codeblock>
                </stepxmp>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N1007E_N1007B_N1002E_N10001" id="238">
                <cmd id="240">Install any applicable system software patches.</cmd>
                <info id="242">
                    <p id="248">For efficient installation, apply patches before starting
                        the configuration process. For details, see the <cite id="208">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade Administration Guide: Managing Software Patches:
                            Installing Patches Locally</cite>.</p>
                </info>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N10058_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="16">
                <cmd id="17">Start the controller configuration script.</cmd>
                <stepxmp id="18">
                    <codeblock id="19"><systemoutput id="264">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="21">sudo config_controller</userinput>
<systemoutput id="265">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade Configuration
======================================
Enter Q at any prompt to abort...</systemoutput></codeblock>
                </stepxmp>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N10072_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="23">
                <cmd id="24">Configure the controller options as requested by the configuration script. </cmd>
                <info id="25">
                    <note id="note_N1007B_N10078_N10071_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="26">
                        <p id="27">The configuration is applied only after all options have been specified.
                            You can safely abort the configuration process at any time by pressing
                            the <nameliteral id="28">Q</nameliteral> key.</p>
                    </note>
                    <p id="29">The following configuration groups are presented. For detailed information,
                        refer to <xref href="jow1419271369349.xml" id="30"/>.</p>
                    <table frame="all" id="table_m21_cmz_cn">
                        <title id="31">Controller Configuration Groups</title>
                        <tgroup cols="2">
                            <colspec colname="c1" colnum="1" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                            <colspec colname="c2" colnum="2" colwidth="1.0*"/>
                            <thead>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="32">
                                        <p id="33">Configuration Group</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="34">
                                        <p id="35">Comments</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="36">
                                        <p id="37">System date and time</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="38">
                                        <p id="39">The date and time as read from the local system
                                            clock.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="40">
                                        <p id="41">Storage</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="42">
                                        <p id="43">The disk space allocations for database, image, and
                                            volume storage. For details, see the <cite id="44">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade Administration Guide</cite>.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="276">
                                        <p id="46">Management network</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="278">
                                        <p id="48">The configuration associated with the internal management
                                            network.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="277">
                                        <p id="280">Board Management Control Network</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="279">
                                        <p id="281">The configuration associated with the board management
                                            control network.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="49">
                                        <p id="50">Infrastructure network</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="51">
                                        <p id="52">The configuration associated with the infrastructure
                                            network.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="53">
                                        <p id="54">External OAM network</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="55">
                                        <p id="56">The configuration associated with the OAM Network.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="57">
                                        <p id="58">Domain Name System (DNS)</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="59">
                                        <p id="60">The IP addresses to use for DNS servers.
                                            The servers must be accessible from the OAM Network.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="61">
                                        <p id="62">Network Time Protocol (NTP)</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="63">
                                        <p id="64">The IP addresses to use for NTP servers.
                                            The servers must be accessible from the OAM Network.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="152">
                                        <p id="154">Licensing</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="156">
                                        <p id="158">The path to the HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade license
                                            file.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="153">
                                        <p id="249">Authentication</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="157">
                                        <p id="159">A temporary password for the Titanium
                                            Server cloud <nameliteral id="178">admin</nameliteral> account. </p>
                                        <note id="note_N1016A_N1015F_N10154_N100C1_N10099_N10090_N10078_N10071_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="70">
                                            <p id="71">This is the password for the cloud
                                                  <nameliteral id="160">admin</nameliteral>
                                                account, not the Linux <nameliteral id="161">wrsroot</nameliteral> account.</p>
                                        </note>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry id="72">
                                        <p id="73">Apply the configuration settings</p>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry id="74">
                                        <p id="75">This is the final question before the
                                            configuration selections are applied. Once you enter
                                                <userinput id="76">y</userinput> to accept
                                            the selected options, the installation script commits
                                            the configuration settings.</p>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                            </tbody>
                        </tgroup>
                    </table>
                </info>
                <stepresult id="77">
                    <p id="78">After a few minutes, the message 
                        <b id="79">Configuration was applied</b>
                    
                        appears.</p>
                </stepresult>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N1023D_N10087_N1002E_N10001" id="162">
                <cmd id="163">Change to the Keystone <nameliteral id="164">admin</nameliteral> account.</cmd>
                <info id="177">
                    <p id="253">Use the <cmdname id="254">source</cmdname> command to become the Keystone
                            <nameliteral id="255">admin</nameliteral> user.</p>
                    <codeblock id="256"><systemoutput id="266">$ </systemoutput><userinput id="258">source /etc/nova/openrc</userinput>
<systemoutput id="267">~(keystone_admin)$ </systemoutput></codeblock>
                </info>
            </step>
            
            <step id="step_N101C3_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="89">
                <cmd id="90">Verify that the HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade controller services are running.</cmd>
                <stepxmp id="91">
                    <codeblock id="92"><systemoutput id="268">~(keystone_admin)$ </systemoutput><userinput id="94">nova service-list</userinput>
<systemoutput id="269">+------------------+--------------+--------+---------+------------+-------+ ...
| Binary           | Host         | Zone   | Status  | Maint Mode | State | ...
+------------------+--------------+--------+---------+------------+-------+ ...
| nova-conductor   | controller-0 | int... | enabled | disabled   | up    | ...
| nova-cert        | controller-0 | int... | enabled | disabled   | up    | ...
| nova-consoleauth | controller-0 | int... | enabled | disabled   | up    | ...
| nova-scheduler   | controller-0 | int... | enabled | disabled   | up    | ...
+------------------+--------------+--------+---------+------------+-------+ ...</systemoutput>
</codeblock>
                </stepxmp>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N101DE_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="96">
                <cmd id="97">Verify that <nameliteral id="98">controller-0</nameliteral> is in the state
                        <nameliteral id="99">unlocked-enabled-available</nameliteral>.</cmd>
                <stepxmp id="100">
                    <codeblock id="101"><systemoutput id="270">~(keystone_admin)$ </systemoutput><userinput id="103">system host-list</userinput>
<systemoutput id="271">+----+--------------+-------------+----------------+-------------+--------------+
| id | hostname     | personality | administrative | operational | availability |
+----+--------------+-------------+----------------+-------------+--------------+
| 1  | controller-0 | controller  | unlocked       | enabled     | available    |
+----+--------------+-------------+----------------+-------------+--------------+</systemoutput></codeblock>
                    <!-- note id="note_N103BB_N103A6_N10392_N10092_N1002E_N10001" id="321">
                        <p id="322">For a minimal two-server configuration, the
                                <nameliteral id="323">availability</nameliteral> is shown as
                                <nameliteral id="324">degraded</nameliteral>. This is because the compute
                            function is not yet configured.</p>
                    </note -->
                </stepxmp>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N10200_N10055_N10028_N10001" importance="optional" id="105">
                <cmd id="106">Synchronize the RAID array.</cmd>
                <info id="107">
                    <p id="108">Normally, the RAID array is already synchronized. If you need to synchronize
                        the RAID array manually, do so now. You may be able to do this by pressing a
                        button on the unit, or using a special key combination on the console
                        keyboard. For details, consult the OEM documentation for the RAID.</p>
                </info>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N10212_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="109">
                <cmd id="110">Using a Web browser, navigate to the OAM floating IP address
                    to verify that the HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade web administration interface is
                    available.</cmd>
                <info id="111">
                    <p id="112">To identify the OAM floating IP address, consult the
                        configuration plan.</p>
                </info>
                <stepresult id="114">
                    <p id="115">The <wintitle id="116">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade</wintitle> login
                        screen appears.</p>
                    <fig id="fig_N10228_N1021D_N1020A_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="117">
                        <title id="118">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade login screen</title>
                        <image alt="Carrier Grade Communication Server login screen" href="jow1404333491396.image" id="image_t5q_4b1_dn" id="119" placement="inline" width="2.5in"/>
                    </fig>
                </stepresult>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N10244_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="120">
                <cmd id="121">Log in using the cloud <nameliteral id="122">admin</nameliteral> account.</cmd>
                <stepresult id="123">
                    <p id="124">The <wintitle id="125">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade</wintitle> web
                        administration interface appears.</p>
                    <fig id="fig_N10251_N10246_N1023B_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="184">
                        <title id="186">HP Helion OpenStack Carrier Grade web administration interface</title>
                        <image alt="Carrier Grade Communication Server web administration interface" href="jow1404333493002.image" id="image_pzt_1ts_g4" id="192" placement="inline" width="5.5in"/>
                    </fig>
                </stepresult>
            </step>
            <step id="step_N1026E_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="129">
                <cmd id="194">In the left-hand pane, on the <uicontrol id="131">Admin</uicontrol> tab, click
                        <uicontrol id="196">Inventory</uicontrol>, and then select the
                        <uicontrol id="133">Hosts</uicontrol> tab.</cmd>
                <stepresult id="198">
                    <p id="135"><nameliteral id="200">Controller-0</nameliteral> is reported in the hosts inventory
                        list.</p>
                    <fig id="fig_N10281_N10277_N10264_N10055_N10028_N10001" id="182">
                        <image alt="Hosts list showing controller-0" href="jow1404333494735.image" id="image_f1p_dtm_jn" id="188" placement="inline" width="5.5in"/>
                    </fig>
                    <!-- note id="note_N10484_N10468_N1044F_N10092_N1002E_N10001" id="325">
                        <p id="326">For a minimal two-server configuration, the <nameliteral id="327">Availability
                                State</nameliteral> is shown as <nameliteral id="328">Degraded</nameliteral>.
                            This is because the compute function is not yet configured.</p>
                    </note -->
                </stepresult>
            </step>
            <!-- step id="step_N1045B_N1008E_N1002E_N10001" id="286">
                <cmd id="287">If you are installing a minimal two-server configuration,
                    configure the compute function on <nameliteral id="288">controller-0</nameliteral>.</cmd>
                <substeps id="substeps_u5p_fth_yr">
                    <substep id="289">
                        <cmd id="290">Configure provider networks.</cmd>
                        <info id="291">
                            <p id="292">For detailed instructions, see <xref href="jow1404333519516.xml" id="293"/>.</p>
                            <p id="294">Provider networks are required so that you can
                                configure data interfaces and unlock the host. By configuring the
                                data interfaces on <nameliteral id="295">controller-0</nameliteral> before you configure <nameliteral id="296">controller-1</nameliteral>, you can avoid the
                                need to swact controllers.</p>
                            <p id="297">Ordinarily, to attach data interfaces, you must lock
                                the affected host. On a host that supports controller and compute
                                functions, this would require a swact to lock the host. The Titanium
                                Server setup for a minimal two-server configuration avoids this by
                                allowing you to define the data interfaces on the unlocked
                                    <nameliteral id="298">controller-0</nameliteral> during
                                initial setup.</p>
                        </info>
                    </substep>
                    <substep id="299">
                        <cmd id="300">Attach the data interfaces to the provider networks.</cmd>
                        <info id="301">
                            <p id="302">For details, see <xref href="jow1426948577755.xml" id="303"/>.</p>
                        </info>
                    </substep>
                    <substep id="304">
                        <cmd id="305">Apply the data interface configuration.</cmd>
                        <info id="306">
                            <p id="307">At the command prompt,  type the following command:</p>
                            <codeblock id="308"><systemoutput id="309">~(keystone_admin)$ </systemoutput><userinput id="310">system compute-config-complete</userinput></codeblock>
                        </info>
                        <stepresult id="311">
                            <p id="312">The configuration is applied and the host is
                                rebooted. </p>
                        </stepresult>
                    </substep>
                </substeps>
            </step -->
        </steps>
        <result id="result_N1028D_N10028_N10001" id="190">
            <p id="140">The host <nameliteral id="141">controller-0</nameliteral> is
                now fully operational. It can be used to initialize all other hosts in the Titanium
                Server cluster.</p>
        </result>
    </taskbody>
</task-wr>